  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Strikes by tens of thousands of miners in this Siberian coal region spread to four more of the Soviet Union's coal fields, Tass reported today.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Kuznetsk, in western Siberia, and Donetsk, in the Ukraine, are the country's two leading coal basins and the strikes amount to the country's worst labor unrest since the 1920s.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Tass today said that the Kuznetsk strike had reached ``a turning point,'' with nine out of 11 mining centers back at work.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   On Wednesday, Tass said that 24,000 strikers in Kuznetsk were back at work and 150,000 remained on strike.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   The government has agreed to most miner demands, including those on pensions and overtime, Gorbachev said.
  </a>
